Miss Stiviano is then said to have claimed she had to return the vehicle, though she did not expand on the comment.

The incident came just days after the former Dodgers manager Tommy Lasorda said of V Stiviano: 'I don't wish that girl any bad luck, but I hope she gets hit with a car.'

He made the remark after being asked about the race row involving Mr Sterling, his friend of 30 years.

A lawsuit filed by Mr Sterling’s estranged wife of 50 years, Rochelle, claimed to show how the Clipper’s owner treated his girlfriend by lavishing her with a series of gifts including the Ferrari, two Bentleys, a Range Rover and a $1.4 million apartment.

Mr Sterling was banned from the NBA after tapes surfaced of him telling Miss Stiviano not to bring black people to his games or pose with them in photos on Instagram.

She had posed in the picture with basketball great Magic Johnson several weeks ago.

